post_text:
A New JSD Organization Structure, Promotions, and a First in JSD History

On August 3, 2020, Superintendent of School, Dr. Art McCoy recommended and the Jennings School District Board (JSD) of Directors unanimously approved the organizational structure below for the district.

Within this action, the JSD Board of Directors unanimously approved the promotion of Dr. Vernice Hicks-Prophet as Assistant Superintendent of JSD and Mrs. Stephanie Alexander as the first Chief Human Resources Officer and Federal Programs of JSD. While we know that all our warriors are special, this action is an acknowledgment of the excellent leadership, stellar service, and positive environment promoted within Jennings School District and beyond by these two outstanding professionals.

On August 3, 2020, Superintendent of School, Dr. Art McCoy recommended and the Jennings School District Board (JSD) of Directors unanimously approved the organizational structure below for the district.

Within this action, the JSD Board of Directors unanimously approved the promotion of Dr. Vernice Hicks-Prophet as Assistant Superintendent of JSD and Mrs. Stephanie Alexander as the first Chief Human Resources Officer and Federal Programs of JSD. While we know that all our warriors are special, this action is an acknowledgment of the excellent leadership, stellar service, and positive environment promoted within Jennings School District and beyond by these two outstanding professionals.

Care STL Health has created a new COVID-19 testing site at Fairview Elementary School, 7047 Emma Ave, St. Louis, MO 63136. There are now two testing sites in the city of Jennings. The new site will open Wednesday, May 6, 2020. The available testing times will be on Tuesdays between 1:00 p.m. – 4:00 p.m. and Wednesdays between 9:00 a.m. – 12:00 p.m. This is essential for community members to further combat the coronavirus. The testing site will be located at the back of Fairview Elementary. Before arriving, individuals must be screened first for symptoms before being tested.

https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/testing-site-coronavirus-north-st-louis-county-schools/63-df9a8518-534e-47ae-b463-ce2ff1530f05

post_text: TEACHER APPRECIATION WEEK!
text: TEACHER APPRECIATION WEEK!

shared_text:
NINENET.ORG
Teaching in Room 9

Jennings School-District
April 28 at 7:14 AM ·

Greetings FB Family!

Dr. Art McCoy proudly sponsored two of our very own teachers to teach the region on the PBS Nine Network Teaching in Room 9 Lessons. Take a look at the pictures in the link. You can tell who they are because Warriors represent Well.

The Nine Network is producing two hours of literacy and math instruction for prekindergarten through fourth grades, weekdays from 12:30–2:30 pm, free of charge on television. The grade-appropriate instruction, taught by committed local educators at home, ensures all kids in our region have access to quality teaching during the academic year shutdown and into the summer, regardless of access to internet or computers.

12:30–2:30 pm, Mondays–Thursdays, on Nine PBS.
Mister Rogers’ Neighborhood on Fridays, followed by repeats of teachers’ lessons.

12:30-1:00 p.m. - Reading, PreK-1st Grade
1:00-1:30 p.m. - Reading, 2nd-4th Grade
1:30-2:00 p.m. - Math, PreK-1st Grade
2:00-2:30 p.m. - Math, 2nd-4th Grade

Nine Network
April 27 at 9:17 AM ·

Beginning TODAY, we are launching "Teaching in Room 9" two hours of literacy and math instruction for students, Pre-K through fourth grade, will be broadcast weekdays from 12:30–2:30 pm, free of charge on Nine PBS.

The grade-appropriate lessons, taught by committed educators from across our region at home, ensure area kids have access to quality teaching during this academic year shutdown and into the summer, regardless of access to internet or computers. All you need is a pencil and paper.

12:30-1:00 p.m. - Reading, PreK-1st Grade
1:00-1:30 p.m. - Reading, 2nd-4th Grade
1:30-2:00 p.m. - Math, PreK-1st Grade
2:00-2:30 p.m. - Math, 2nd-4th Grade

Join us again on Tuesday, April 7th at 7pm on Facebook Live as we honor our administrators and advisors of the year! #MASCatHOME

Jennings Senior High School and the St. Louis Area Student Council Members nominated Dr. Art McCoy for the Gateway District Administrator of the Year at the annual meeting last November of 2019 at Mehlville High School. Dr. Art McCoy was selected by the St. Louis Area Student Council Advisors as the 2020 recipient of this tremendous honor. Unfortunately, with the MASC State Convention being canceled last month due to COVID 19, they were unable to acknowledge this achievement at Timberland High School in March of 2020. The Missouri Association of Student Councils will, however, broadcast on Facebook Live for everyone to see the district advisor and administrator honorees from around the state. MASA will recognize Dr. Art McCoy for this honor tonight at 7 pm on Facebook live. I hope that you're able to tune in!

https://www.facebook.com/mascstuco/?__tn__=%2Cd%2CP-R&eid=ARAMng5H2B6l5l0iKeNYUEQoe0gU1jVkCTGuD1pAMReP8hNGQpbwRl9GXiwxFZd1V1uQ1lvRuLMPBwRg

Jennings Senior High School and the St. Louis Area Student Council Members nominated Dr. Art McCoy for the Gateway District Administrator of the Year at the annual meeting last November of 2019 at Mehlville High School. Dr. Art McCoy was selected by the St. Louis Area Student Council Advisors as the 2020 recipient of this tremendous honor. Unfortunately, with the MASC State Convention being canceled last month due to COVID 19, they were unable to acknowledge this achievement at Timberland High School in March of 2020. The Missouri Association of Student Councils will, however, broadcast on Facebook Live for everyone to see the district advisor and administrator honorees from around the state. MASA will recognize Dr. Art McCoy for this honor tonight at 7 pm on Facebook live. I hope that you're able to tune in!

Governor Mike Parson
January 9 at 10:43 AM ·

Honored to have Secretary Ben Carson from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development be our featured speaker at the 2020 Governor's Prayer Breakfast.

This year's theme was, "Walk In The Light," and Secretary Carson shared a powerful story from his days as a pediatric neurosurgeon when walking in faith was one little boy's only hope of healing.

Nearly 600 guests attended this year, and we got to enjoy a very special performance from the Jennings High School Concert Choir.

My hope is that each of us remember to walk in the light this year.

St. Louis Area Foodbank
December 5, 2019 at 5:01 PM ·

Today, we officially opened three new School Food Markets. These markets are part of a new initiative aimed at addressing hunger by providing nutritious food to kids and their families in convenient, familiar, and safe locations. They are currently being piloted in the Jennings School District (Missouri) and Cahokia Unit School District #187 (Illinois), with plans to expand to three additional sites in 2020. Funding for the School Food Markets program comes from the Bayer Fund, the philanthropic arm of Bayer.

The Foodbank will stock each market regularly with a selection of fresh foods and staple grocery items.

More info can be found in the official press release - https://www.bayer.us/en/newsroom/press-releases/article/?id=123372

STLARCHS
October 30, 2019 at 2:35 PM ·

ARCHS' CEO Wendell Kimbrough recently earned his "Afterschool Superhero" cape as a panelist at the Show Me Afterschool Community Conversation at Gateway MST Middle School.

Afterschool professionals and law enforcement from around the state gathered on Saturday, October 26th to discuss the critical investment in children to keep them safe from 2-6 p.m., when juvenile crime is more likely to occur. It was an honor to sit alongside Moline ACRES P.D. Chief Gregory Moore, Missouri AfterSchool Network, many members of the Jennings School District community, Unleashing Potential St. Louis, and Saint Louis Public Schools. ARCHS is dedicated to going beyond the discussion to continue the investment and strategic support at 29 afterschool sites in our area.

The Green Center
July 3, 2019 at 4:33 PM ·

During the weeks of June 17-20 and June 24-27, The Green Center was busy participating in this summer's UPOP St. Louis Program! The Urban Populations Outreach Program provides field trips to Missouri’s beautiful parks and historic sites for hundreds of urban youths from the St. Louis, Kansas City and Columbia urban cores and several southwest Missouri communities.

The UPOP-St. Louis Program is a partnership between the The Green Center, Missouri Parks Association, Missouri State Parks and the Jennings School District.

And a special thank you to the Missouri American Water for donating water bottles!

This year, 6th grade students from Northview Elementary and 4th-6th graders from Fairview Elementary participated in programming.

THANK YOU to all of our partners for making this year's program a SUCCESS!

post_text:
YOUTH Academy MSHP Program 2019

What an awesome law enforcement and leadership experience for nearly 28 youth across Missouri with the Missouri State Highway Patrol (MSHP). This year, we added value to this program as well as learned by including two St. Louis County Police Officers, a Jennings teacher, and 7 Jennings students to participate and represent the St. Louis region. These students received high school elective course credit and CPR training, which is state-required for Missouri seniors as part of their high school curriculum, and much more. Their lives were changed forever.

Dr. McCoy is working with leaders of the St. Louis PD to create C.A.P.L.E. Camp, which stands for Careers and Pathways in Law Enforcement for up to 50, 16 to 18-year-olds from St. Louis County, St. Louis City, and East St. Louis to receive this experience as well as mentoring, and more in law enforcement.

Thank you to the Steward Family Foundation and David Steward, Jr. for his vision, passion, and support.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lb4iiKHzVco

YOUTUBE.COM
YOUTH Academy MSHP Program at EAGLE SKY CAMP 2019
text:
YOUTH Academy MSHP Program 2019

What an awesome law enforcement and leadership experience for nearly 28 youth across Missouri with the Missouri State Highway Patrol (MSHP). This year, we added value to this program as well as learned by including two St. Louis County Police Officers, a Jennings teacher, and 7 Jennings students to participate and represent the St. Louis region. These students received high school elective course credit and CPR training, which is state-required for Missouri seniors as part of their high school curriculum, and much more. Their lives were changed forever.

Dr. McCoy is working with leaders of the St. Louis PD to create C.A.P.L.E. Camp, which stands for Careers and Pathways in Law Enforcement for up to 50, 16 to 18-year-olds from St. Louis County, St. Louis City, and East St. Louis to receive this experience as well as mentoring, and more in law enforcement.

Thank you to the Steward Family Foundation and David Steward, Jr. for his vision, passion, and support.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lb4iiKHzVco

YOUTH Academy MSHP Program at EAGLE SKY CAMP 2019

Last month history was made! The first ever Tri-M Music (Honor Society) has started in the Jennings School District.

Tri-M Music Honor Society chapter opens up a world of opportunities for students who have already shown themselves to be academically capable and musically gifted. Through performance and community service, they’ll develop confidence, creativity, critical thinking, compassion, and a host of other leadership skills sure to serve them well in school and beyond.
